<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia</i> <i>farinosa</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Agave</i> <i>deserti</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>bigelovii</i>, <i>Echinocereus</i> <i>engelmannii</i>, <i>Eriodictyon</i> <i>crassifolium</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Ferocactus</i> <i>cylindraceus</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Mirabilis</i> <i>laevis</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>apiana</i>. Emergent trees or tall shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Fouquieria</i> <i>splendens</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is open with seasonal annuals. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Encelia farinosa</i> > 1% absolute cover in the shrub canopy and with greater cover than other woody species (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Encelia farinosa</i> > 50% relative cover, or > 30% with <i>Ambrosia dumosa</i> in the shrub canopy (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
		
		<li><i>Encelia farinosa</i> > 50% relative cover, or > 30% with <i>Artemisia californica</i> in the shrub canopy (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alluvial fans, bajadas, colluvium, rocky hillsides, slopes of small washes and rills. Soils are well drained, rocky, and may be covered by desert pavement.  </div>
</div>

        
