<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Encelia farinosa </i>is a short-lived subshrub that lives up to 30 years. It leafs out and flowers when moisture is available. It reproduces by seed and weakly sprouts from damaged stems (Tesky 1993b). The species does not tolerate sandy or clay-rich soils; it is common on steep, rocky sites, especially south-facing slopes. <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Encelia farinosa </i>alliance, as defined here, represent the drought-tolerant end of the coastal sage scrub and the creosote bush scrub types. Many of the stands considered part of the <i>Encelia farinosa </i>and <i>Larrea tridentata </i>series in the first edition are now included in the <i>Larrea tridentata-Encelia farinosa </i>alliance. The presence or absence of <i>L. tridentata </i>frequently relates to the standâ€™s disturbance history. Some <i>E. farinosa </i>stands are long-lived on harsh rocky sites in the desert and inner coastal mountains, while undisturbed stands can give way to <i>L. tridentata </i>types under less demanding conditions in the desert. <i>E. farinosa </i>rapidly colonizes roadsides and other disturbed areas. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
