    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-b, Cd). Stands commonly occur on granitic slopes of the Peninsular Ranges on the lower slopes below 700 m. A fire history in the Palm Springs area (Brown and Minnich 1986) suggests that <i>Larrea tridentata-Encelia farinosa</i> stands were converted to those of <i>E. farinosa</i> by multiple recent fires. Several large stands exist near San Gorgonio Pass, in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b), and in the Coachella Valley and East Mesa-Sand Hills subsections (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ab-f, Ah-p). Stands are widespread but less extensive in this section than are those of the <i>Larrea tridentata-Encelia farinosa</i> alliance. Most are disturbance-related. Stands occur on the Marine Corps Air Ground Combat Center (Minnich et al. 1993) and generally in the central and eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands are common on slopes and well-drained upper bajadas and alluvial fans throughout the section. Stands occur on granitic, schistic, and volcanic substrates, especially in the Chocolate Mountains and Valleys subsection (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fd-e). Stands occur on volcanic breccia west of Panamint Springs and on south-facing slopes in the Grapevine Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi-l, Bp). Stands occur in the Peninsular and Transverse ranges usually on south and west-facing aspects at low elevations, on old alluvial fans of the Santa Ana River area near Mentone, generally in the western subsections as part of coastal sage scrub (Kirkpatrick and Hutchinson 1977), as well as in the Perris Valley area and Cahuilla and San Jacinto mountains (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The coincidence of non-native <i>Bromus madritensis </i>or <i>B. rubens </i>invasion and human-related fires impact the structure and diversity of stands in this alliance. Managers should identify and monitor core areas where grass cover is absent or sparse in the warm deserts, and fires should be excluded at all times of the year. Similarly, short fire return intervals (e.g., 10 years or less) often degrade the inner coastal scrub stands of <i>Encelia farinosa; </i>fires should be maintained at longer intervals. </div>
</div>

    

    

